Watching this so soon after the death of grandparent was painful. I hope to revisit it again when more healing is done. Really impactful work being done here. Yang is able to capture the act of crying in a way I’ve never seen before. So honest and lost.

Review: My parents found this on Netflix. Looking at the poster alone, I knew I was in for a British hallmark equivalent. Anyways, my dad gave this five stars

Absolutely blown away by this. Todd Haynes reaches to the core of something I’ve not really seen him achieve before. Echoes of Peter Strickland and De Palma’s work move through this, creating something sinister, harrowing and sometimes hilarious. Some devastating work by Melton, juxtaposed by the extreme high wire act being done by Moore and Portman. Tonal gymnastics and power shifts are continuously occurring deep in the grounds of the story, but you don’t even realize it until it’s too late.…

Movie: Attack on Titan The Final Chapters: Special 2
Review: Having a hard time putting into words how monumental this show was for me. Ten years with it and at the end, it proves to be one of the most interesting explorations of humanity and what we’re capable of doing to one another. What started as a humans vs monsters story, slowly inverts on itself, defining the cycle of violence we inflict upon ourselves. It seems poignant that it came out when it did with everything happening in the world.…
